article.description: Rookie Swin Cash had 16 points and 10 rebounds as the Detroit Shock beat the New York Liberty 66-63 on Wednesday for their second win of the season.

article.headline: Liberty can't hold Detroit's Cash in check
article.linkText: Shock hold off Liberty for second win of season
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Richie Adubato had never been through anything like it in his long coaching career. A canceled flight caused him and his New York Liberty players to spend hours waiting at Newark Airport on Tuesday. Then after returning home for a few hours of sleep, they had to fly to Detroit on Wednesday morning for an 11:30 a.m. tip-off against the Shock. "I've had bad travel nights before, but never with an 11:30 start time," the Liberty coach said after a 66-63 loss. "We had to get up at 3:30 and fly here, so we were pretty much in a coma at the start of the game." The Liberty (10-9) got off to a slow start, missing 14 of their first 16 shots. "I'm proud of my team for coming as close as they did," Adubato said. "We basically spotted them a dozen points before we were even awake." Rookie Swin Cash had 16 points and 10 rebounds as Detroit (2-16) improved to 2-6 since Bill Laimbeer replaced Greg Williams as coach last month. "That was a good win for us," Laimbeer said. "We wanted to come home and re-establish to ourselves that we are on the right track." Barbara Farris added a career-high 14 for the Shock. "I'm just glad I could contribute," said Farris, who moved into the lineup when Wendy Palmer was traded to Orlando on Monday. "I knew New York was solid in the post, so I wanted to play some tough defense." Detroit, which led 28-22 at halftime, started the second half with a 13-4 run to take a 41-27 lead with 14:30 left, but couldn't put the Liberty away. Vickie Johnson scored four points in a 9-2 run that pulled New York within five at 43-38 with 12 minutes left. The Liberty got as close as 54-50 with 5:16 left, but couldn't get closer until Johnson's layup made it 64-62 with 36 seconds left. After Cash and Tari Phillips each split a pair of free throws, New York fouled Ayana Walker, who also made 1-of-2 from the line to make it 66-63. Cash forced a jump ball with Crystal Robinson at the other end, and New York gained possession but couldn't get a 3-point attempt off before the buzzer. "We did everything we possibly could to win this game," Cash said. "We played really hard." Adubato was also upset by a decision by the officials, who waved off a basket early in the second half because of an offensive foul on Cash, then gave Detroit the points several minutes later. The officials decided that the basket should have counted because the player who committed the loose-ball foul was not the one who scored the basket, but Adubato disagreed with the call and the late decision. "I don't understand how you can decide four minutes later to overrule the call," he said. "That cost us the game." Robinson led New York with 17 points, while Phillips finished with 14 and Johnson 12. Game notes
Neither team had a player named to the Eastern Conference All-Star reserves, which were announced Wednesday. New York's Teresa Weatherspoon and Phillips were voted in as starters. ... The win ended Detroit's five-game losing streak to New York. ... Elaine Powell, traded for Palmer on Monday, scored eight points in her Detroit debut.
